The '''Safe Schools Declaration''' is an inter-governmental political commitment that was opened for endorsement by countries at an international conference held in [[Oslo]], [[Norway]], on 28-29 May 2015.<ref name="LocalNo">{{cite web |url=http://www.thelocal.no/20150529/oslo-meet-pledges-to-protect-schools|title=Oslo meet pledges to protect schools in war|publisher=The Local No|date=2015-05-29}}</ref><ref name=IrishTimes>{{cite web |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/education/state-urged-to-sign-up-to-safe-schools-declaration-1.2220275|title=State urged to sign up to Safe Schools Declaration |publisher=Irish Times |author=Joe Humphreys |date=2015-05-20}}</ref><ref name="TageS">{{cite web |url=http://www.tagesspiegel.de/politik/deklaration-zum-schutz-von-schulen-menschenrechtler-empoert-ueber-deutschland/11787154.html|title=Deklaration zum Schutz von Schulen: Menschenrechtler empört über Deutschland|publisher=Der Taggespiegel|author=Ulrike Scheffer |date=2015-05-17}}</ref><ref name="28mill">{{cite web |url=http://www.elmundo.es/internacional/2015/05/29/55687eb722601d9c688b457c.html|title=28 millones de niños sin educación por culpa de la guerra|publisher=El Mundo|author=Maria Fluxa |date=2015-05-29}}</ref><ref name="MFAreport">{{cite web |url=https://www.regjeringen.no/no/aktuelt/safe-school-declaration/id2456474/|title=Rapport fra konferansen om beskyttelse av utdanning i konfliktsituasjoner|publisher=Norwegian Ministry of Foreign Affairs|date=2015-10-05}}</ref><ref name=BBC>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-32916422|title=Campaign to stop attacks on schools |author=Sean Coughlan |publisher=BBC News |date=2015-05-29}}</ref> The Declaration provides countries the opportunity to express political support for the protection of students, teachers, and schools during times of [[armed conflict]]; the importance of the continuation of education during armed conflict; and the implementation of the [[Military Use of Schools#Guidelines for Protecting Schools and Universities from Military Use during Armed Conflict|''Guidelines for Protecting Schools and Universities from Military Use during Armed Conflict'']].<ref name="MFAreport"/><ref name="SSD">{{cite web |url=https://www.regjeringen.no/globalassets/departementene/ud/vedlegg/utvikling/safe_schools_declaration.pdf |title=Safe Schools Declaration|publisher=Norwegian Ministry of Foreign Affairs|date=2015-05-29}}</ref><ref name=IPS>{{cite web |url=http://www.ipsnews.net/2015/06/countries-commit-to-protecting-education-during-conflict/|title=Countries Commit to Protecting Education During Conflict |author=Roger Hamilton-Martin |publisher=Inter Press Service News Agency |date=2015-07-02}}</ref>
<br />

As of November 2018, 82 countries have endorsed the Safe Schools Declaration, which remains open for additional countries to join.<ref name=StatesEndorsed>{{cite web |url=http://www.safeschools.no/|title=States that have endorsed the Safe Schools Declaration |publisher=Norwegian Ministry of Foreign Affairs}}</ref><ref name="Gendorse">{{cite web |url=http://www.protectingeducation.org/guidelines/support|title=Safe Schools Declaration Endorsements|publisher=Global Coalition to Protect Education from Attack|access-date=2015-10-13}}</ref><ref name="MFAreportIntro">{{cite web |url=https://www.regjeringen.no/globalassets/departementene/ud/vedlegg/hum/the-oslo-conference-report_e-950e.pdf|title=Introduction by the Norwegian Minister of Foreign Affairs Mr. Børge Brende|author=Børge Brende|publisher=Norwegian Ministry of Foreign Affairs|date=2015}}</ref> The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Norway)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Norway]] is the depositary of endorsements.<ref name=Endorse>{{cite web |url=http://www.safeschools.no/|title=Endorsement of the Safe Schools Declaration |publisher=Norwegian Ministry of Foreign Affairs}}</ref><ref name="eletter">{{cite web |url=http://www.protectingeducation.org/sites/default/files/documents/template_endorsement_letter.pdf|title=Letter for Endorsing the Safe Schools Declaration|access-date=2015-10-12}}</ref>
<br />

On March 28-29, 2017, the ministries of [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Worship|foreign affairs]] and [[Ministry of Defense (Argentina)|defense]] of [[Argentina]] co-hosted the Second International Safe Schools Conference in [[Buenos Aires]].<ref name="SSC2">{{cite web |url=http://www.mrecic.gov.ar/en/second-international-conference-safe-schools-0|title=Second International Conference on Safe Schools|publisher=Argentine Ministry of Foreign Affairs}}</ref>

In May 2017, the United Nations [[Secretary-General of the United Nations|Secretary General]], [[António Guterres]], urged all Member States to endorse the Safe Schools Declaration.

On April 24, 2018, Spain announced that it will host the Third International Safe Schools Conference in 2019.

== Drafting ==
The Safe Schools Declaration was developed through consultations with states led by the ministries of foreign affairs of Norway and [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Worship|Argentina]] between January and May 2015.<ref name="MFAreportIntro"/><ref name=process>{{cite web |url=http://www.protectingeducation.org/draft-lucens-guidelines-protecting-schools-and-universities-military-use-during-armed-conflict |title=Guidelines for Protecting Schools from Military Use:Next steps |publisher=Global Coalition to Protect Education from Attack}}</ref> <br />

Representatives from more than 60 countries attended the conference launching the Safe Schools Declaration in 2015, along with the [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Norway)|Norwegian Foreign Minister]] [[Børge Brende]], [[Minister of Defence (Norway)|Norwegian Defence Minister]] [[Ine Marie Eriksen Søreide]], and [[Ziauddin Yousafzai]] the father of [[Nobel Peace Prize]] laureate [[Malala Yousafzai]].<ref name="MFAreport"/><ref name="IPS"/><ref name="sixty">{{cite web |url=https://www.regjeringen.no/en/aktuelt/protecting-education/id2414002/|title=Broad support for protecting education from attack|publisher=Norwegian Ministry of Foreign Affairs|date=2015-05-29}}</ref>

Representatives from more than 80 countries attended the second Safe Schools Conference in Buenos Aires in 2017.<ref name="SafeSchoolsBA">{{cite web |url=http://www.protectingeducation.org/news/over-80-states-gather-discuss-safe-schools-declaration-buenos-aires-conference|title=Over 80 states gather to discuss Safe Schools Declaration at Buenos Aires conference|publisher=Global Coalition to Protect Education from Attack|date=2017-03-30}}</ref>

== Contents and Commitments ==
<blockquote>
"The impact of armed conflict on education presents urgent humanitarian, development and wider social challenges. Worldwide, schools and universities have been bombed, shelled and burned, and children, students, teachers and academics have been killed, maimed, abducted or arbitrarily detained. Educational facilities have been used by parties to armed conflict as, ''inter alia'', bases, barracks or detention centres. Such actions expose students and education personnel to harm, deny large numbers of children and students their right to education and so deprive communities of the foundations on which to build their future. In many countries, armed conflict continues to destroy not just school infrastructure, but the hopes and ambitions of a whole generation of children." <br />
– Opening paragraph of Safe Schools Declaration<ref name=SSD />
</blockquote>

The Safe Schools Declaration describes the immediate and long-term consequences of attacks on students, teachers, schools, and universities, and the [[Military Use of Schools|military use of schools]] and universities, during times of armed conflict. It contrasts this with the positive and protective role that education can have during armed conflict.<ref name=SSD /><br />

By joining the Declaration, states formally endorse the ''Guidelines for Protecting Schools and Universities from Military Use during Armed Conflict'' and commit to “bring them into domestic policy and operational frameworks as far as possible and appropriate.”<ref name=SSD /><br />

The Declaration also contains a number of other commitments aimed at strengthening the prevention of, and response to, attacks on education during armed conflict, including by: collecting reliable data on attacks and military use of schools and universities; providing assistance to victims of attacks; investigating allegations of violations of national and [[international law]] and prosecuting perpetrators where appropriate; developing and promoting “conflict sensitive” approaches to education; seeking to continue education during armed conflict; and supporting the work of the [[United Nations]] on the children and armed conflict agenda.<ref name=SSD /><br />

Lastly, the Declaration is a framework for collaboration and exchange, as endorsing states also agree to meet on a regular basis to review implementation of the Declaration and use of the ''Guidelines''.<ref name=SSD /><br />

